RemarkThe Whimbrel 1 well is located in an area of pinchouts and truncations and was drilled as a stratigraphic/structural test. The well was spudded on April 5, 1974, and a total depth of 6,754 feet was reached on May 4, 1974.A sequence of sediments ranging in age from Recent to Upper Permian was penetrated.The Lower Jurassic and Upper Triassic sections were absent. The Lower Cretaceous and Middle Triassic sections contained several sandstones zones of potential reservoir quality, and Cretaceous Bathurst Island and Lower Triassic Mt. Goodwin shale sections provided top and bottom seals for these potential reservoir lithologies. Minor gas shows were recorded while drilling the Lower Cretaceous section, and log analysis showed several thin log anomalies. Subsequent F.I.T. test recovered only mud filtrate and minor amounts of formation water. The interval was considered to be water-bearing only.Further small gas shows were noted while drilling the Upper Permian section. Several sidewall samples at the top of the Upper Permian section had minor fluorescence and cut. The zone was tested by F.I.T. and produced only formation water. The interval was considered to have residual shows only.Whimbrel 1 is located offshore in the Bonaparte Gulf Basin, Western Australia, 34 km SE of Osprey 1 and 129 km WNW of Plover 1.A moderately thick sequence of sedimentary rocks ranging in age from Upper Permian to Tertiary was drilled at this location. Minor amounts of gas were recorded in the Mesozoic section and in the Upper Permian. Patchy fluorescence also occurred in the Upper Permian but there were no indications of oil. The postulated pinnacle reef was not present.Whimbrel 1.. drilled offshore.. in the Bonaparte Gulf - Timor Sea area. The well, in concession WA-15P (Western Australia)is located 21 miles southeast of the Osprey 1 well and 80 miles west-northwest of the Plover 1 well.
